        <div class="section_text section_background">
            <h2>We are in sea-rious trouble.</h2>
            <p>Rising sea levels, a critical consequence of climate change, primarily occur due to two primary factors: thermal expansion and melting ice caps and glaciers. As global temperatures rise, thermal expansion takes place, causing seawater to expand and occupy more space. Additionally, the melting of polar ice caps, glaciers, and ice sheets contributes significantly to the influx of water into the oceans. The increased meltwater from these frozen reservoirs adds to the volume of seawater, further elevating sea levels. Human-induced activities, such as the burning of fossil fuels and deforestation, release greenhouse gases into the atmosphere, amplifying the greenhouse effect and leading to global warming. This warming, in turn, accelerates the melting of ice masses and exacerbates the expansion of seawater, resulting in the alarming rise of sea levels worldwide. The consequences of rising seas are extensive, threatening coastal communities with more frequent and severe flooding, eroding shorelines, salinization of freshwater sources, and displacement of populations, emphasizing the urgent need for concerted global action to mitigate climate change and its impacts on sea level rise.</p>
        </div>
